from the nonprofit gods.

508
00:42:33.178 --> 00:42:36.138
<i>And he's about to do a sit-down
with</i> The Times <i>too.</i>

509
00:42:36.139 --> 00:42:37.265
<i>Give us some love.</i>

510
00:42:37.266 --> 00:42:39.433
Wait. he's doing an interview? When?

511
00:42:39.434 --> 00:42:40.518
<i>Right now.</i>

512
00:42:40.519 --> 00:42:42.563
They're setting up here
in the office as we speak.

513
00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:47.024
- Do I look good? Do I look good?
- Yes.

514
00:42:47.025 --> 00:42:48.568
Hey.

515
00:42:48.569 --> 00:42:49.695
I'm coming in.

516
00:42:52.990 --> 00:42:54.324
So much for taking it easy.

517
00:42:54.992 --> 00:42:58.578
Max. you're the
ultimate victim of what you have called

518
00:42:58.579 --> 00:43:00.664
the criminal injustice system.

519
00:43:01.248 --> 00:43:04.835
But I have to ask.
why did you plead guilty?

520
00:43:06.920 --> 00:43:09.714
Well... I was under pressure.

521
00:43:09.715 --> 00:43:11.716
Mm-hmm. From who?

522
00:43:11.717 --> 00:43:13.092
That's the past.

523
00:43:13.093 --> 00:43:15.595
Tabitha. today. all I want is

524
00:43:15.596 --> 00:43:20.349
to help other people that face injustice.
like Ruben Ramirez. right?

525
00:43:20.350 --> 00:43:25.438
And thank God for groups like SJLP
that fight for Ruben.

526
00:43:25.439 --> 00:43:27.607
It's hard to believe
you don't dwell on the past.

527
00:43:27.608 --> 00:43:29.776
But what's the past. anyway?

528
00:43:30.611 --> 00:43:34.113
A museum full of-of-of dead things.

529
00:43:34.114 --> 00:43:37.034
Well. you had
an unusual childhood. didn't you?

530
00:43:37.784 --> 00:43:40.328
You didn't meet your father
till you were 13 years old?

531
00:43:40.329 --> 00:43:44.957
Yeah. My father.

532
00:43:44.958 --> 00:43:47.877
Okay. my father was an American soldier

533
00:43:47.878 --> 00:43:51.924
stationed in the south of Spain.

534
00:43:52.424 --> 00:43:54.217
- He had his fun.
- Okay.

535
00:43:54.218 --> 00:43:58.554
He got a pretty young Basque woman
pregnant and she didn't want a kid.

536
00:43:58.555 --> 00:44:02.309
So. uh. you know. it was not...

537
00:44:03.143 --> 00:44:07.523
It was no... no picnic growing up with her.
You know what I mean?

538
00:44:08.732 --> 00:44:10.650
But at least her cooking was pretty good.

539
00:44:10.651 --> 00:44:13.027
That's why I went
into the restaurant business.

540
00:44:13.028 --> 00:44:15.322
So. at least I have that.

541
00:44:15.906 --> 00:44:19.158
And. uh. yeah.

542
00:44:19.159 --> 00:44:22.579
And then. when I was 13.
she killed herself.

543
00:44:23.580 --> 00:44:28.460
Yeah. Boop. Jumped off a building.

544
00:44:30.170 --> 00:44:35.509
And. uh. I was sent to America to live
with my father.

545
00:44:36.510 --> 00:44:39.012
No more family in Spain.
never been back there.

546
00:44:40.430 --> 00:44:44.100
And when I got
to North Carolina...

547
00:44:44.101 --> 00:44:47.562
I-I-I-I-I don't know.
I was... I was. like. lost.

548
00:44:47.563 --> 00:44:49.730
I-I didn't even speak English. you know?

549
00:44:49.731 --> 00:44:51.190
Did your dad teach you?

550
00:44:51.191 --> 00:44:56.988
No. No. No. No. my father had a new life.

551
00:44:56.989 --> 00:44:58.740
Uh. he was breeding dogs.

552
00:44:59.741 --> 00:45:01.368
Had a... had a new family

553
00:45:02.244 --> 00:45:05.414
and he did not want some

554
00:45:06.665 --> 00:45:13.630
bastard mongrel. uh. around. I guess.

555
00:45:14.506 --> 00:45:15.799
Oh. how painful.

556
00:45:22.014 --> 00:45:25.767
<i>It was tough. but I had to adapt.</i>

557
00:45:26.393 --> 00:45:27.978
<i>And I did adapt.</i>

558
00:45:28.687 --> 00:45:30.856
<i>I learned to be strong.</i>

559
00:45:33.901 --> 00:45:35.736
<i>It gave me a sense of morality.</i>

560
00:46:02.221 --> 00:46:05.598
You know. uh. an old friend said
to me just the other day

561
00:46:05.599 --> 00:46:09.810
that. uh. it's never too late to fix
what we've broken

562
00:46:09.811 --> 00:46:13.440
and all my life. I wanted just one thing.

563
00:46:14.107 --> 00:46:15.316
My own family.

564
00:46:15.317 --> 00:46:19.946
And I could see it in my head.
A wife. a daughter. a son.

565
00:46:19.947 --> 00:46:22.658
Maybe a house with a big backyard.

566
00:46:23.200 --> 00:46:24.576
A swimming pool. maybe.

567
00:46:25.202 --> 00:46:27.954
Even a cat passing by. I don't know.

568
00:46:27.955 --> 00:46:30.039
Uh. uh. maybe it's too late for that.

569
00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:33.377
I don't know. but I was an impatient boy.

570
00:46:34.461 --> 00:46:36.296
but I'm a patient man.

571
00:46:37.297 --> 00:46:39.090
And I'm just getting started.

572
00:46:48.809 --> 00:46:49.810
What?

573
00:47:06.285 --> 00:47:07.369
Motherfucker.

574
00:47:08.620 --> 00:47:13.584
Everything okay? Anna? Hello?

575
00:47:16.128 --> 00:47:20.382
Didn't we just say we were gonna focus
on Zack? Just try to get back to normal?

576
00:47:23.427 --> 00:47:24.928
Yeah. You're right.

577
00:47:26.805 --> 00:47:28.056
You don't sound convinced.

578
00:47:32.936 --> 00:47:35.564
Is there any way Max could know
about what we did?

579
00:47:37.858 --> 00:47:39.109
No one knows but us.

580
00:47:39.693 --> 00:47:41.653
No one will
because no one needs to. right?

581
00:47:42.946 --> 00:47:43.947
Right.

582
00:47:45.324 --> 00:47:46.742
We did what we thought was right.

583
00:48:08.138 --> 00:48:10.807
You're looking at a four-bedroom.
four-and-a-half-bath.

584
00:48:11.391 --> 00:48:12.391
The kitchen.

585
00:48:12.392 --> 00:48:15.646
uh. watch your step here.
has all new stainless steel appliances.

586
00:48:16.563 --> 00:48:19.900
Oh. and the private terrace leads
to a beautiful garden.

587
00:48:20.734 --> 00:48:25.155
All of the staging furniture is available
for purchase. at a price.

588
00:48:26.365 --> 00:48:28.824
And the bonus room above the garage

589
00:48:28.825 --> 00:48:31.662
could be used as a home office
or a playroom.

590
00:48:32.746 --> 00:48:38.167
Is it just you? Any kids?
Other than your fur baby here.

591
00:48:38.168 --> 00:48:40.462
He's not gonna leave any business
in the house. is he?

592
00:48:41.713 --> 00:48:42.798
No.

593
00:48:43.549 --> 00:48:47.261
Um. what about a short escrow?

594
00:48:48.178 --> 00:48:50.889
And I'll waive all the contingencies.

595
00:48:52.057 --> 00:48:54.101
I could see what's possible.

596
00:48:55.185 --> 00:48:59.439
I'm sorry. I don't mean to be rude.
but I know who you are.

597
00:49:00.482 --> 00:49:01.483
Can you afford this?

598
00:49:02.317 --> 00:49:07.489
Don't worry about money.
I'm gonna be compensated for my pain.

599
00:49:08.365 --> 00:49:10.117
Okay.

600
00:49:10.617 --> 00:49:14.246
Is there someone
at your bank that I could chat with?

601
00:49:15.289 --> 00:49:18.624
You know what they say. Trust but verify.

602
00:49:18.625 --> 00:49:22.379
Yeah. You know another thing they say?

603
00:49:23.672 --> 00:49:26.090
That if you are falsely convicted.

604
00:49:26.091 --> 00:49:31.220
you will feel a different kind of PTSD
than other prisoners.

605
00:49:31.221 --> 00:49:37.185
because you lose faith in all the systems
that were supposed to protect you.

606
00:49:37.186 --> 00:49:39.438
like-like laws and money.

607
00:49:40.397 --> 00:49:42.816
So. the only system you know
is the system of fuck you.

608
00:49:44.818 --> 00:49:47.236
But. Gloria. you're not in that system.

609
00:49:47.237 --> 00:49:49.530
You're not. You're still in the other one.

610
00:49:49.531 --> 00:49:51.449
- Correct?
- Yes.

611
00:49:51.450 --> 00:49:54.244
Don't worry. my dear.
I'll get you that info.

612
00:49:55.162 --> 00:49:57.623
And I'll come in over asking.

613
00:49:59.750 --> 00:50:02.628
How much over asking?

614
00:50:05.088 --> 00:50:08.967
Can you give me a minute
to get the feel of the place?

615
00:50:10.969 --> 00:50:12.262
Of course.

616
00:50:19.811 --> 00:50:22.731
Alone. if you don't mind.

617
00:50:33.617 --> 00:50:36.495
All the way outside. please.
